WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:20.920
I work at RStudio in the Tidyverse team, and today I'll be talking about interactivity

00:00:20.920 --> 00:00:24.200
and programming in the Tidyverse.

00:00:24.200 --> 00:00:32.320
So this is about the notion of data masking in R, which is this idea that you can blend

00:00:32.320 --> 00:00:37.439
the data with the workspace, so that you can work with the columns in your data frames

00:00:37.439 --> 00:00:41.840
as if they were objects in your workspace.

00:00:41.840 --> 00:00:47.360
And I think that's a really great and unique feature of R, that it helps to turn ideas

00:00:47.360 --> 00:00:51.799
into software because you're directly working with your data, rather than worrying about

00:00:51.799 --> 00:00:55.080
the data structure that it is in.

00:00:55.080 --> 00:01:02.040
On the other hand, it does make some things more difficult, and in particular, it makes

00:01:02.040 --> 00:01:08.919
it more difficult to reuse code, to write functions around data masking functions.

00:01:08.919 --> 00:01:16.360
So we have made progress in the tooling to solve that issue, and also in the teaching,

00:01:16.360 --> 00:01:18.480
in our approach to teaching.

00:01:18.480 --> 00:01:23.879
So if you have learned a little bit about TidyEval before, we'll see some new concepts

00:01:23.879 --> 00:01:24.879
here.

00:01:24.879 --> 00:01:28.440
The concepts that you have learned before are still relevant.

00:01:28.440 --> 00:01:34.760
We still use the bang-bang operator all the time when we create our tools, but this should

00:01:34.760 --> 00:01:41.879
be considered lower-level tools, and now we are going to see a higher-level approach.

00:01:41.879 --> 00:01:50.680
So I would like to talk a little bit about the history of data masking in R. So in 1998,

00:01:50.680 --> 00:01:57.160
the blue book was published that defined the S language, which is the ancestor of R, and

00:01:57.160 --> 00:02:00.959
a lot of the things that we still use were in that book.

00:02:00.959 --> 00:02:07.239
And one of the first manifestations of data masking was in the attach function, which

00:02:07.239 --> 00:02:13.119
allows you to take a dataset and attach it to the search path the same way that you do

00:02:13.119 --> 00:02:14.720
with a package.

00:02:14.720 --> 00:02:19.320
So that's a little bit different from data masking, but it's still the idea that the

00:02:19.320 --> 00:02:24.679
data frame is the important scope, and that if you are working interactively with R, you

00:02:24.679 --> 00:02:29.520
want to be able to work with the data directly.

00:02:29.520 --> 00:02:40.119
So attach is not the recommended way of working with data now, but a few years later, the

00:02:40.119 --> 00:02:45.440
white book was published, and it was about all of the statistical modeling functions

00:02:45.440 --> 00:02:49.919
that we still use in R now, so like the LM function.

00:02:49.919 --> 00:02:55.320
And the way that it works is that they took a data frame and a formula, and in the formula,

00:02:55.320 --> 00:02:56.320
you have data masking.

00:02:56.320 --> 00:03:01.919
You can refer to your columns directly.

00:03:01.919 --> 00:03:09.919
And then R was being developed in the 90s, and Peter Dalgaard, who is a member of R-Core,

00:03:09.919 --> 00:03:14.520
published the frame tools package, which was really foundational for R and for the tidyverse

00:03:14.520 --> 00:03:17.160
and for DeepLayer.

00:03:17.160 --> 00:03:22.520
And so as you can see, you had the subset frame function, the select frame function

00:03:22.520 --> 00:03:24.479
and modify frame.

00:03:24.479 --> 00:03:31.279
And these are the same kind of function that we have in DeepLayer, like filter, select,

00:03:31.279 --> 00:03:36.479
and mutate, and you could use data masking to filter rows.

00:03:36.479 --> 00:03:41.240
You could select columns and modify columns inside the data frame.

00:03:41.240 --> 00:03:47.240
And that was the first operation of selections, which is a little bit different from data

00:03:47.240 --> 00:03:48.679
masking.

00:03:48.679 --> 00:03:53.399
So in particular, you can use the column operator to select a range of variables that

00:03:53.399 --> 00:03:59.479
are consiguous in your data frame, and other features that make it really easy to select

00:03:59.479 --> 00:04:01.440
columns.

00:04:01.440 --> 00:04:07.559
So these were integrated in R. Subset and select were merged into one single function.

00:04:07.559 --> 00:04:11.360
Modify became transform.

00:04:11.360 --> 00:04:21.200
And then there were relatively few developments on data masking in base R. The with function

00:04:21.200 --> 00:04:24.959
was included, and the within function a few years later.

00:04:24.959 --> 00:04:29.839
But by and large, most of the developments happened in package space.

00:04:29.839 --> 00:04:35.200
So in 2006, the data table package was released for the first time.

00:04:35.200 --> 00:04:41.920
And one of the things that it did besides performance is that it allowed you to use

00:04:41.920 --> 00:04:49.880
data masking in I to subset rows, and you could use data masking in J, but also selections

00:04:49.880 --> 00:04:52.559
to select columns.

00:04:52.559 --> 00:04:55.959
Then 2014, DeepLayer was released.

00:04:55.959 --> 00:05:02.399
So very similar to the ideas that were in the frame tools package, but with the objective

00:05:02.480 --> 00:05:08.679
to really push data masking in a much more comprehensive API.

00:05:08.679 --> 00:05:15.480
So what was the reason that development of the data masking slowed down in base R?

00:05:15.480 --> 00:05:20.880
I think we can find the answer in the documentation topics for subset and transform.

00:05:20.880 --> 00:05:26.559
And if you read those, you will see this warning that they are really convenience functions

00:05:26.559 --> 00:05:34.959
intended for use interactively, that nonstandard evaluation can have unanticipated consequences.

00:05:34.959 --> 00:05:42.160
So I think what they mean by that is that it's about the ambiguity between data variables,

00:05:42.160 --> 00:05:46.399
so variables that are in your data frame, and environment variables, those that are

00:05:46.399 --> 00:05:50.799
in your workspace and that you have assigned with the R operator.

00:05:50.799 --> 00:05:55.200
And this ambiguity causes two different problems that are distinct but related.

00:05:55.600 --> 00:06:00.359
First, you can get unexpected masking from data variables.

00:06:00.359 --> 00:06:05.959
And secondly, data variables cannot get through function arguments, and that makes it difficult

00:06:05.959 --> 00:06:09.359
to create functions around data masking functions.

00:06:09.359 --> 00:06:15.679
And so we are going to see solutions that we offer in the Tidyverse to solve these issues.

00:06:15.679 --> 00:06:18.079
So first about unexpected masking.

00:06:18.079 --> 00:06:21.040
That's about the problem.

00:06:21.040 --> 00:06:25.200
So let's say that you have created an object N in your workspace.

00:06:25.200 --> 00:06:26.920
It contains a number.

00:06:26.920 --> 00:06:29.480
And you have a data frame with an X column.

00:06:29.480 --> 00:06:34.920
And you want to modify it, create a new column that divides the column X by the number inside

00:06:34.920 --> 00:06:41.559
of N. And the problem is that the data frame is really a moving part.

00:06:41.559 --> 00:06:46.519
And if you are using the same code with different data frames, maybe they don't contain the

00:06:46.519 --> 00:06:47.640
same columns.

00:06:47.640 --> 00:06:56.359
And if you get a data frame that has a column N, then the column has precedence over the

00:06:56.359 --> 00:06:57.640
object in the workspace.

00:06:57.640 --> 00:07:04.880
The column masks the object in the workspace, and you get the wrong result.

00:07:04.880 --> 00:07:10.399
So that's not a big problem if you are working interactively through your script doing an

00:07:10.399 --> 00:07:15.119
analysis because you know what kind of objects you have in the workspace.

00:07:15.119 --> 00:07:19.119
You know the columns that are in your data frames.

00:07:19.119 --> 00:07:25.760
But if you are writing production code, that can be an issue because your same code will

00:07:25.760 --> 00:07:31.079
be used across many different data frames from different users.

00:07:31.079 --> 00:07:35.679
So the solution here is to be explicit when you are writing production code.

00:07:35.679 --> 00:07:40.700
And to do that, you use the .data pronoun or the .inf pronoun.

00:07:40.700 --> 00:07:46.579
And these pronouns are available in all of the data masking functions in the tidyverse.

00:07:46.579 --> 00:07:53.739
And so here we are, again, modifying the data frame, but this time we are dividing .data$X

00:07:53.739 --> 00:08:00.220
by .inf$N. And now we are completely explicit about where the data comes from, and we have

00:08:00.220 --> 00:08:03.859
resolved the ambiguity.

00:08:03.859 --> 00:08:09.059
So the second problem that data variables cannot get through function arguments.

00:08:09.059 --> 00:08:13.700
That makes it difficult to create functions around tidyverse pipelines.

00:08:13.700 --> 00:08:19.660
So let's say that we have this minby function where we have some data.

00:08:19.660 --> 00:08:26.399
We group by one variable, and we summarize by taking the average of another variable.

00:08:26.399 --> 00:08:33.179
And so we take one data frame and two variables that we pass to group by and summarize.

00:08:34.020 --> 00:08:40.099
And so if we call this minby function with data variables like species, we get this error

00:08:40.099 --> 00:08:43.340
that column by is unknown.

00:08:43.340 --> 00:08:48.859
So what happens here is that inside the function, we are referring to this function argument,

00:08:48.859 --> 00:08:51.979
which is an environment variable, by.

00:08:51.979 --> 00:08:56.559
And when you call the function, you are supplying a data variable species.

00:08:56.559 --> 00:09:03.059
And that's how R gets confused and it doesn't know what your element.

00:09:03.099 --> 00:09:09.299
So the solution is to tunnel the data variable through the environment variable.

00:09:09.299 --> 00:09:15.460
And to tunnel a data variable, you use this new operator curly curly, which was added

00:09:15.460 --> 00:09:19.140
in RLANG last year.

00:09:19.140 --> 00:09:26.099
And that allows the color of your function to use a data variable, and it will get forwarded

00:09:26.099 --> 00:09:32.380
through the environment variable and evaluated in the data frame as it should.

00:09:32.380 --> 00:09:39.179
So one other issue that you might have is that we have hard-coded the result name here.

00:09:39.179 --> 00:09:43.419
We have given it the name of AVG for average.

00:09:43.419 --> 00:09:50.619
But maybe you want to have something that changes with the input.

00:09:50.619 --> 00:09:56.979
So a very new feature in RLANG that just got here last week is that you can now use glue

00:09:56.979 --> 00:10:01.960
strings on the left-hand side of the walrus operator.

00:10:01.960 --> 00:10:06.840
So the syntax is a little bit different from the glue package, because you have to use

00:10:06.840 --> 00:10:13.559
double curly, and that allows you to tunnel a data variable inside the string.

00:10:13.559 --> 00:10:24.119
And then you get a more relevant result name in the resulting data frame.

00:10:24.119 --> 00:10:29.039
One issue with tunneling is that it causes data masking to propagate.

00:10:29.039 --> 00:10:34.400
So now your function is also a data masking function, because, you know, you can supply

00:10:34.400 --> 00:10:37.440
data variables in it.

00:10:37.440 --> 00:10:41.479
And that means that the users of your function will have to know about that.

00:10:41.479 --> 00:10:43.760
They will have to know about the ambiguity.

00:10:43.760 --> 00:10:49.960
If they are writing production code, they will have to know about the curly curly operator.

00:10:49.960 --> 00:10:54.440
They want to write a function around your function.

00:10:54.559 --> 00:11:04.039
So one question is, is there a way to easily create functions but without the data masking

00:11:04.039 --> 00:11:06.039
propagation?

00:11:06.039 --> 00:11:12.080
So if we go back to the dot data pronoun that we have subsetted with the dollar operator

00:11:12.080 --> 00:11:18.960
with constant column names, species and simple dot width, and let's say that now you want

00:11:18.960 --> 00:11:25.559
to subset column names which are in variables, then you use the double bracket operator

00:11:25.559 --> 00:11:28.599
as you would in normal R code.

00:11:28.599 --> 00:11:35.859
And now that means that we are using environment variables that contains the column names.

00:11:35.859 --> 00:11:38.039
And so you build your function around that.

00:11:38.039 --> 00:11:43.679
You take your data frame, you take the two variables, and now you have a completely normal

00:11:43.679 --> 00:11:48.520
function that takes column names as strings, and you don't have any data masking anymore.

00:11:48.520 --> 00:11:54.280
Which can be better when you are working in an organization and working with coworkers

00:11:54.280 --> 00:12:01.159
which maybe don't know about data masking, the tidyverse, or all that.

00:12:01.159 --> 00:12:07.400
And in this case, if you want to customize the result name, you use again the glue string,

00:12:07.400 --> 00:12:15.219
but this time with the normal single curly operator.

00:12:15.219 --> 00:12:18.940
So that's how you deal with these two problems.

00:12:18.940 --> 00:12:23.340
If you have unexpected masking and you're worried about that, use the dot data and dot

00:12:23.340 --> 00:12:26.140
inf pronoun to disambiguate.

00:12:26.140 --> 00:12:33.179
And if you want to create functions and deal with the problem of taking arguments which

00:12:33.179 --> 00:12:39.179
might contain data variables, you tunnel them with the double curly operator or you subset

00:12:39.179 --> 00:12:45.380
the data with the double bracket if you want to take column names as strings instead.

00:12:45.380 --> 00:12:46.940
So what about selections?

00:12:46.940 --> 00:12:50.419
As we have seen, selections are a bit different.

00:12:50.419 --> 00:12:56.099
They are kind of a separate sublanguage, especially in the tidyverse functions.

00:12:56.099 --> 00:13:01.419
And the reason for that is that data variable in selections, so for example, if you use

00:13:01.419 --> 00:13:07.940
the select function in the player, but also pivot wider, pivot longer in tidy or use selections.

00:13:07.940 --> 00:13:13.219
And in this selection, data variables represent the locations inside the data frame.

00:13:13.219 --> 00:13:18.340
And that's actually the reason why that you can use the column operator, because if you

00:13:18.340 --> 00:13:24.299
say column name, column mass, that's really the same as writing one, column three, and

00:13:24.299 --> 00:13:30.780
you create this sequence of locations from which we know where to get the variables from.

00:13:30.780 --> 00:13:36.719
But that means that ambiguity is much less an issue when you are working with selections.

00:13:36.719 --> 00:13:43.200
So let's say that you have a character vector of column names, which is assigned in the

00:13:43.200 --> 00:13:46.440
name environment variable.

00:13:46.440 --> 00:13:52.320
And the Star Wars data frame also contains a column that's called name.

00:13:52.320 --> 00:13:56.880
But if you write select name, that's a data variable.

00:13:56.880 --> 00:14:00.679
So you will be selecting the column name.

00:14:00.679 --> 00:14:04.640
If you want to disambiguate and use the character vector that you have saved in your object

00:14:04.640 --> 00:14:07.760
in your workspace, you use all of.

00:14:07.760 --> 00:14:14.679
So if you are familiar with one of, all of is a new function that's a little bit stricter

00:14:14.679 --> 00:14:18.840
and that has better properties.

00:14:18.840 --> 00:14:27.039
If you, when you use all of, it means that you want, you are expecting all the columns

00:14:27.039 --> 00:14:29.880
in the character vector to be in the data frame, and if they are not there, you will

00:14:29.880 --> 00:14:30.880
get an error.

00:14:30.880 --> 00:14:33.799
Whereas one of was throwing a warning instead.

00:14:33.960 --> 00:14:39.679
So you have a little bit more strict here.

00:14:39.679 --> 00:14:44.760
So if you have a, if you want to create a function around the selection function, you

00:14:44.760 --> 00:14:53.080
just take the data frame and then the variable, a variable containing the column names, and

00:14:53.080 --> 00:14:57.119
you just use select all of and the function elements.

00:14:57.119 --> 00:15:03.200
And then you have a normal function and you can call them with character vectors.

00:15:03.200 --> 00:15:06.479
But you can also use the double curly operator.

00:15:06.479 --> 00:15:13.159
And in this case, it means that you are tunneling the selection from across the function.

00:15:13.159 --> 00:15:19.479
And in this case, in the same way that if you use the curly curly with a data masking

00:15:19.479 --> 00:15:25.679
verb, and you create a data masking function, then your function becomes a selection function.

00:15:25.679 --> 00:15:33.140
And that means that your user can call, can use the selection helpers like start with.

00:15:34.080 --> 00:15:35.080
So that's it.

00:15:35.080 --> 00:15:44.859
That's, those are the new features and the, that we'd like, like, I'm sorry.

00:15:44.859 --> 00:15:45.859
What?

00:15:45.859 --> 00:15:46.859
Sorry.

00:15:46.859 --> 00:15:48.859
I'm crushing them.

00:15:48.859 --> 00:15:49.859
Yeah.

00:15:49.859 --> 00:15:56.859
So if you want to disambiguate the data variables from the environment variables, you use the

00:15:56.859 --> 00:15:59.859
data, you use the data pronoun and the dot inf.

00:15:59.859 --> 00:16:05.179
If you have data masking, if you are using a selection function, you use all of.

00:16:05.179 --> 00:16:12.020
And in case you want to tunnel data variables and selection, you use the curly curly operator.

00:16:12.020 --> 00:16:13.020
Thanks.

00:16:13.020 --> 00:16:20.500
Thank you, Lionel.

00:16:20.500 --> 00:16:21.979
We do have some questions here.

00:16:21.979 --> 00:16:22.979
Yeah.

00:16:22.979 --> 00:16:28.140
The first one says, are these new features to replace or be alternatives to cool and

00:16:28.140 --> 00:16:30.260
beta and bang, bang?

00:16:30.260 --> 00:16:38.179
No, like, like, these are higher level features that are meant to be easier to use for people

00:16:38.179 --> 00:16:43.340
that don't want to get into metaprogramming and learning these hard skills.

00:16:43.340 --> 00:16:49.739
But all the lower level programming tools are here to stay, and we, we use them to build

00:16:49.739 --> 00:16:51.179
these tools ourselves.

00:16:51.179 --> 00:16:52.179
Great.

00:16:52.179 --> 00:16:57.739
Also, can you clarify the difference between all of and everything with select?

00:16:57.739 --> 00:16:59.059
I'm sorry?

00:16:59.059 --> 00:17:02.500
The difference between the all of that you just showed and everything.

00:17:02.500 --> 00:17:03.500
Yeah.

00:17:03.500 --> 00:17:07.219
So everything means that you want to select everything.

00:17:07.219 --> 00:17:12.180
And all of means that you are only selecting the columns that are inside the character

00:17:12.180 --> 00:17:13.739
vector that you supply.

00:17:13.739 --> 00:17:14.739
Thank you.

00:17:14.739 --> 00:17:21.219
The last one I have here, is there a timetable for implementing curly curly curly or super

00:17:21.219 --> 00:17:22.219
stash?

00:17:22.219 --> 00:17:23.219
No.

00:17:23.219 --> 00:17:24.219
No.

00:17:24.219 --> 00:17:25.219
That's not, that's not planned.

00:17:25.219 --> 00:17:26.219
Not planned.

00:17:26.219 --> 00:17:27.219
Okay.

00:17:27.699 --> 00:17:31.500
And the last one is, is all elements of the syntax supported by dbplyr and sparklyr?

00:17:31.500 --> 00:17:34.020
Sorry, can you repeat this?

00:17:34.020 --> 00:17:37.260
Are these supported by dbplyr and sparklyr?

00:17:37.260 --> 00:17:38.260
Yeah.

00:17:38.260 --> 00:17:43.540
dplyr for sure, sparklyr I don't know about that, but I would guess so because they're

00:17:43.540 --> 00:17:44.979
probably using tidiva.

00:17:44.979 --> 00:17:45.979
I agree.

00:17:45.979 --> 00:17:46.979
Yeah.

00:17:46.979 --> 00:17:52.380
And last one, does curly, curly work with multiple variables?

00:17:52.380 --> 00:17:53.380
No.

00:17:53.380 --> 00:17:55.140
Only, only one function argument.

00:17:55.140 --> 00:18:00.339
So you're really, it's really meant to use with function arguments inside functions only.

00:18:00.339 --> 00:18:01.339
Great.

00:18:01.339 --> 00:18:02.339
Thank you so much.

00:18:02.339 --> 00:18:02.339


